{
  "texts": [
    "Based on these prior gaps, the section then provides an in-depth critique of the DSA across interrelated dimensions-legal, psychological, and ethical-to reveal inconsistencies and unexamined assumptions that warrant ongoing empirical assessment and regulatory refinement.",
    "Specifically, the trajectory leading up to the DSA represents a gradual acknowledgment of self-governance limitations around complex threats like disinformation, giving way to formal multi-stakeholder cooperation and binding regulations.",
    "However, tensions persist around reconciling such binding rules with evidentiary burdens, accuracy, oversight, and proportionality amidst pressing societal calls for action.",
    "Regulatory antecedentsTo contextualize the DSA's approach, we trace the regulatory evolution governing online platforms and some of the struggles in addressing complex, international disinformation campaigns.",
    "The EU, in fact, had an initial reliance on self-regulation, which exhibited flaws potentially enabling threats to proliferate."
  ]
}